  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/sqa-gradation2",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2023 R1 is a commercially validated FEA solver with documented V&V procedures, version control, and release testing. FDA and DePuy Synthes internal SQA records confirm software qualification to ISO 13485 requirements. Gradation 2 achieved: solver is commercially qualified with documented testing history."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/code-verification-gradation2",
      "rationale": "Benchmark patch tests and standard beam bending verification problems were executed against analytical solutions. Maximum deviation from analytical solutions was 0.8%, well within the accepted 2% threshold. Gradation 2 achieved: code verification performed against known analytical benchmarks with documented pass criteria."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/discretization-gradation2",
      "rationale": "Mesh convergence study performed across three refinement levels (coarse, medium, fine) for both screw and vertebral body surrogate components. Richardson extrapolation applied; grid convergence index (GCI) < 1.5% for all QoIs. Final mesh selected at medium refinement where further refinement changes QoI by < 0.5%. Gradation 3 achieved: systematic convergence study with GCI quantification."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/solver-error-gradation1",
      "rationale": "Newton-Raphson iterative solver convergence confirmed with force residual < 1e-4 and displacement residual < 1e-5 for all load steps. Energy balance checked at each increment. No divergence or convergence warnings observed across all 11 model instances. Gradation 2 achieved: solver convergence monitored and confirmed for all simulation runs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/use-error-gradation2",
      "rationale": "Model setup reviewed by independent analyst at each of the three participating organizations (FDA, Ansys, DePuy Synthes). Boundary conditions, material assignments, contact definitions, and load application independently verified against ASTM F1717 protocol. Cross-organization comparison of model inputs confirmed consistency. Gradation 2 achieved: independent review of model setup completed."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/model-form-gradation2",
      "rationale": "Linear elastic material model with isotropic titanium alloy properties (Ti-6Al-4V, E=114 GPa, ν=0.34) selected based on literature precedent for pedicle screw F1717 testing where strains remain below yield in the construct body. Contact between screw and UHMWPE block modeled with frictional contact (μ=0.2). Model form assumptions documented and justified against COU loading regime. Gradation 2 achieved: model form assumptions documented with supporting justification."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/model-inputs-gradation2",
      "rationale": "Material properties sourced from certified material test reports for the specific Ti-6Al-4V lot used in physical specimens. Geometric inputs derived from CMM measurements of actual test specimens (dimensional tolerance ±0.01 mm). Sensitivity analysis performed on elastic modulus (±10%), friction coefficient (±50%), and screw insertion depth (±1 mm); QoI sensitivity < 3% for all parameters. Gradation 3 achieved: inputs traceable to measurements with sensitivity analysis quantifying input uncertainty influence."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/test-samples-gradation2",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs tested across two independent laboratories. All specimens from the same manufacturing lot with documented dimensional inspection. UHMWPE vertebral body surrogates from a single supplier batch. Sample preparation protocol documented per ASTM F1717. Gradation 2 achieved: samples characterized and traceable to defined manufacturing and preparation protocols."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/test-conditions-gradation2",
      "rationale": "Testing performed under a single set of ASTM F1717 prescribed conditions (room temperature, 2 mm/min displacement rate, ambient humidity). No variation in test conditions was explored. This limits the ability to assess model validity across a range of conditions relevant to the COU. Gradation 1 achieved (below required Gradation 2): single test condition only, no parametric variation of test environment. This shortfall is noted as an accepted limitation consistent with the description in the COU.",
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/decision/cou1-accepted-2026/factor/test-conditions"
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/input-equivalency-gradation2",
      "rationale": "FEA model inputs (geometry, material properties, boundary conditions, loading) verified to match experimental specimen parameters through direct measurement comparison. CMM geometry data used to update FEA geometry for each specimen. Material property inputs matched to certified test reports from the same lot. Documented equivalency table prepared and reviewed by all three organizations. Gradation 2 achieved: systematic equivalency verification between simulation inputs and experimental conditions documented."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/output-comparison-gradation2",
      "rationale": "Quantitative comparison performed for all three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) using both percentage difference metric (<10% acceptance bound) and normalized validation metric E/uval (<1.96 acceptance bound). All QoIs passed both acceptance criteria across all three modeling organizations. E/uval values: stiffness 0.82, yield force 1.14, force at 40 mm 0.97. Gradation 3 achieved: quantitative comparison with uncertainty-normalized validation metric applied to all QoIs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/qoi-relevance-gradation2",
      "rationale": "QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) directly correspond to the regulatory submission requirements for spinal implant mechanical performance under ASTM F1717. These metrics are established indicators of clinical performance risk and are the quantities used in the regulatory decision. Gradation 2 achieved: QoIs are directly linked to the COU decision variables with documented justification."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/validation-relevance-gradation2",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments replicate the exact ASTM F1717 protocol specified in the COU, using the same screw design, dimensions, material, and surrogate vertebral body as the intended submission testing. The validation domain directly encompasses the COU domain with no extrapolation required. Multi-laboratory participation (FDA, independent CRO) strengthens generalizability of validation findings. Gradation 2 achieved: validation activities directly represent the COU without extrapolation, with multi-laboratory confirmation."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/decision/cou1-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/org/fda-cdrh-osel",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for COU1 (non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw compression-bending FEA) is accepted at Medium assurance level. All 13 V&V 40 factors were assessed. Twelve of thirteen factors meet or exceed their required credibility levels. One factor (Test conditions, Factor 9) achieved Gradation 1 against a required Gradation 2, reflecting the single-condition ASTM F1717 test protocol. This shortfall is consistent with standard industry practice for this device class and test standard, and is mitigated by the high concordance of results across two independent laboratories and three independent modeling organizations. Quantitative validation metrics (E/uval < 1.96 and QoI difference < 10%) were satisfied for all three quantities of interest (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) across all modeling organizations. The multi-organization modeling exercise (FDA, Ansys, DePuy Synthes) provides additional confidence in model form and implementation correctness. Model risk level 3 with Medium model influence and Medium decision consequence yields an overall Medium assurance requirement, which is met by the evidence package. The FEA modeling framework is accepted as a credible tool for predicting ASTM F1717 compression-bending performance of the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw construct within the defined COU.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z",
    "hasOffsetRationale": {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/decision/cou1-accepted-2026/offset/test-conditions",
      "type": "OffsetRationale",
      "refersToFactor": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/decision/cou1-accepted-2026/factor/test-conditions",
      "justification": "Placeholder offset rationale (Phase 2.5 v0.5.11 corpus regen) for 'Test conditions' factor shortfall on this Accepted decision. The W-AR-02 rule's intent is to flag Accepted-despite-shortfall findings that are NOT documented; structurally well-formed but not substantively meaningful. Real-world V&V 40 cases (e.g., Nagaraja et al. 2024 §4) record the offsetting evidence here."
    }
  },
